[1] UK (HPR)
Date: Fri 12 Jul 2013
Source: Health Protection Report, Volume 7 No 28 [edited]
http://www.hpa.org.uk/hpr/archives/2013/news2813.htm#msls


A total of 188 cases of measles were confirmed in England with onset in May 2013, making a total of 1168 cases since the start of the year [2013]. This is the lowest monthly total recorded since November 2012 and follows a prolonged period with monthly figures around the highest recorded levels since enhanced surveillance commenced in 1994. The North East and North West regions continue to report the highest number of cases, followed by London. The age group most affected in May 2013 was 10-14 year olds (52/188, 28 percent), consistent with a shift towards this age group when compared to the previous 4 years.

Amongst cases this year [2013], 231 (20 percent) were associated with secondary school outbreaks. Small outbreaks have also been reported from "hard-to-reach" populations with known low coverage such as the travelling community and the ultra-Orthodox Jewish community in north London. Overall, 230 (20 percent) of all cases in 2013 were admitted to hospital, of which 35 reported complications including pneumonia, meningitis and gastroenteritis.

Most of the cases in May 2013 that have been genotyped have been shown to be MVs/Taunton.GBR/27.12/[D8], which has been circulating in England since July 2012.

As previously reported, the shift towards secondary school age groups in 2013 is likely to be explained by the fall in coverage of MMR that occurred between 1999 and 2005. To reduce the risk of larger outbreaks of measles in the next academic year, Public Health England, the Department of Health and NHS England announced an MMR catch-up programme in late April 2013. The campaign has targeted children aged between 10 and 16 years who have a record of none or incomplete MMR vaccination. Returns from the NHS Areas Teams confirm that almost 5000 practices have already signed up to participate in the programme. The service involves sending letters from general practices inviting under-vaccinated children to attend the surgery for vaccination. The primary target population was the estimated 8 percent of that age group (around 300 000 individuals) who had received no vaccine. Secondary targets included a similar number of children in that age group who had received one dose of MMR and a similar number of under-vaccinated individuals in other age groups.

Around 200 000 extra doses have been ordered, and preliminary data from 1276 practices (around 16 percent of the total for England) suggests that the percentage of children in this age group with no record of having received MMR has declined by around 1.3 percent. This is consistent with a national reduction in the total of unvaccinated 10-16 years olds of around 56 000, although data from a larger number of practices is awaited. If this increase was to be replicated nationally, this would represent about half the estimated number of vaccinations required to reach the campaign objective of ensuring that at least 95 percent of 10-16 year olds had received at least one dose of MMR. In addition, the number of children recorded as partially vaccinated has fallen by a similar proportion. Although most vaccination has been conducted in primary care, school campaigns have been conducted in response to local outbreaks and are being planned for the next school year in many areas to ensure as many children as possible are vaccinated.

