[2] UK (NE England)
Date: Wed 10 Jul 2013
Source: The Northern Echo [edited]
http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/10539249.Measles_case_continue_to_fall_but_Middlesbrough_remains_top_of_the_table_for_towns_affected/


The rate that measles is spreading across the North East has started to decline, according to the latest figures.

Monthly data show 43 cases of the preventable, infectious disease were reported in May 2013 compared to 112 in April 2013, which suggests the rate of increase may be declining. However, the latest data takes the North East total for 2013 at the end of May 2013 to 368, which compares to only 2 confirmed cases reported during the same period last year [2012]. Middlesbrough remains the worst affected area with 19 of the 43 new cases being people from the town.

The report estimates that there are thousands of young people aged between 10 and 16 who remain unvaccinated, and measures will remain in place to target the "priority group." Dr Roberta Marshall, director of the North East Public Health England Centre, said: "Thanks to the hard work of local health teams, we are making good progress towards the 95 per cent target, but there still remains a large number of 10-16 year olds, together with many younger children and young adults, who are under-vaccinated.

--
