[4] UK (Scotland)
Date: Sat 13 Jun 2013
Source: The Evening Telegraph [edited]
http://www.eveningtelegraph.co.uk/news/local/ongoing-measles-outbreak-in-tayside-1.111842


Watchdog Health Protection Scotland confirmed that Tayside and Fife are at the centre of a 19-strong "cluster" of confirmed measles cases. NHS Tayside has also reported 7 additional cases of the "sometimes fatal" disease in the local area. These numbers account for more than half of the confirmed 48 measles cases in Scotland since January [2013]. The board's health protection team has been sending out letters to people who have had contact with confirmed sufferers warning them to check their vaccination history and to be on the lookout for symptoms. The number of measles cases across the country is on the rise, with 3 times as many suspected cases reported this year [2013] as there were over the same period in 2012. The "ongoing" outbreak, which so far has infected at least 19 people, is within a Travelling [Roma] group that has been moving around Tayside and Fife.

A Health Protection Scotland report, which analysed all confirmed and suspected measles cases in the 1st 6 months of 2013, said: "There were 3 clusters of cases. One cluster -- 19 laboratory confirmed and one probable case -- occurred in the traveller community in Fife and Tayside and is ongoing." The locations of the 2 other Scottish clusters, the 1st consisting of 6 confirmed cases and the 2nd of 2 confirmed cases, was not identified. However, the outbreaks were revealed to have been in a healthcare setting and a school.

In a notification letter, NHS Tayside's Dr Daniel Chandler said people can develop symptoms as long as 21 days after the initial exposure period. The consultant in public health medicine said: "Measles is a viral infection that can spread very easily from person to person. People are infectious for 5 days before the rash appears, and so people can pass on the infection before they realise they have measles." Uptake of the MMR vaccine in Tayside is slightly higher than the Scottish average, with some 95.4 percent of 2 year olds having had the inoculation.

[Byline: Beth Cherryman]

