[6] Canada (ONT)
Date: Fri 12 Jul 2013
Source: Hamilton Spectator thespec.com [edited]
http://www.thespec.com/news-story/3889240-burlington-shoppers-may-have-been-exposed-to-measles-as-another-case-reported/


Dr. Bob Nosal, Halton's Medical Officer of Health, says another case of measles has been identified, bringing the region's recent total to 5. He said the latest case is in Oakville, and it's believed the patient came in contact with the disease at a health-care location. Nosal said the 1st 3 cases involved Burlington children from the same family, while the 2 latest cases are adults.

He said since the disease is more commonly passed among children, he had hoped it would have been the end of the outbreak. His concern now is that the latest patient may have exposed a number of people to the disease during a shopping trip to the Target store at Burlington Mall on 6 Jul 2013 between noon and 3 p.m. "We wouldn't be issuing a news release if we knew we could get the information out there to everyone who may have come in contact with it," Nosal said. Nosal said the patient also visited the Freshco store at 2501 3rd Line in Oakville on the morning of 6 Jul 2013 and then attended mass at St. Paul the Apostle Roman Catholic Church in Burlington on Sun 7 Jul 2013 at 8 p.m.

Children and adults who have been properly vaccinated for measles should have no concern, Nosal added. "In this day and age, we shouldn't be seeing measles," Nosal explained. "When we do see it, we act very aggressively. It's a very communicable disease." The Halton health department is asking anyone who fears they may have measles to call in advance to a doctor's office, walk-in clinic or emergency department in an effort to limit any exposure to staff and other patients.

[Byline: Dave Churchill]

