[7] Canada (BC)
Date: Fri 12 Jul 2013
Source: The Colonist, The Canadian Press [edited]
http://www.timescolonist.com/life/health/measles-outbreak-in-whistler-and-pemberton-health-officials-suggest-vaccination-1.522445


A measles outbreak in 2 more British Columbia communities could be a sign of more cases to come, says a medical health officer who is urging parents to get their children vaccinated.

Dr. Paul Martiquet of the Vancouver Coastal Health Authority said on Fri 12 Jul 2013 that he's concerned that 8 cases of the highly contagious disease have been confirmed in the province since mid-June 2013. "It's been 3 years since we have seen measles (in B.C.)," he said. Martiquet said one in every 3000 Canadians with measles dies of the infection.

He said the 4 cases identified this week in Whistler and Pemberton are not linked to the 4 cases diagnosed in Bowen Island and the North Shore last month [June 2013], raising questions about the outbreak's origins. "It is possible that it's been brought in internationally, or it's possible that it's just been circulating in the community without us knowing," he said, adding it may be more likely that an overseas visitor to a tourism destination such as Whistler had the disease.

"This a wake-up call," Martiquet said. "Measles is a killer. It can be prevented by a safe and effective vaccine, and we are requesting parents -- especially with their newborns and infants -- to avail themselves to the childhood vaccine series for measles that starts at 12 months, and a 2nd dose at 18 months."

Officials recommend vaccinations for adults and for children over a year old if they not have received the 2 necessary doses. Anyone who has already had the infection is immune, and officials say adults born before 1970 are likely to be immune.

The last outbreak of measles in British Columbia was in 2010, when 70 cases were diagnosed following the Winter Olympics.

